[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/business-designer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/business-designer-6-7)

See also [Testing conditions, multiple test data sets](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-create-and-edit-templates-short-instruction-guide#testing-conditions-multiple-test-data-sets), and [Connect the template with XML test](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-create-and-edit-templates-short-instruction-guide#connect-the-template-with-xml-test-data) [data](#_bookmark29).

Templates are only linked to test data sets, so that the data fields are available and the generation of documents can be tested. The actual linking to the real data set is only done when the template is used.

You can create the connection under *Data *&gt; *Manage Test Data*.

> Note:

*A new template must first be saved, only then the connection to a test data file can be created.*

A data input must always be defined to include a test case. If you add a Test Case without data input (under *Test Cases *with the + symbol), the program will therefore first ask you to add a data input variable.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

You can change the names for test cases and data inputs. Use the Edit symbol for this purpose.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Note:

*The name for the data input is part of the XPath expression of data fields and should therefore be changed before inserting data fields if necessary.*

To **disconnect the data connection**, simply remove the test case and/or data input with the trash icon.

If **several test cases **are needed, you can add more XML files with the same structure to the same data input.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

The data fields can also come from **different data sources**, i.e. two or more XML files with different structures are included, e.g. one for the customer address and another for the purchase-related customer data. If different data sources are used, add a separate data input for each file.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Any number of data inputs can be defined per test case and vice versa.

You may also have multiple test cases in one XML file. In this case, the first data set is always taken when testing. To test specifically with another data set, you can change the number in XPath specifications, e.g. in the expression *customer/person[1]/name change to â€¦ /person[2]/name.

> Note:

*The location of the linked XML files is stored internally with a relative path. If the files are moved, the program may no longer be able to find them. In this case you must first remove the test cases and then select the XML files again with the Assign _button._*

![](data:image/png;base64,)
